vars: {
  d2-config: {
    layout-engine: elk
    theme-id: 6
  }
}
shape: sequence_diagram
UserCode: "User Code\n(Event Loop)"
Kernel: "Linux Kernel\n(epoll + socket)"
OS: "OS FD Allocator"
step1: {
  UserCode -> Kernel: "accept4(listen_fd, NULL, NULL, SOCK_NONBLOCK)\n→ returns fd=7"
  Kernel -> UserCode: "fd=7 (new client connection)"
}
step2: {
  UserCode -> Kernel: "epoll_ctl(epfd, EPOLL_CTL_ADD, fd=7,\n{EPOLLIN, data.fd=7})\n→ fd=7 added to interest set"
}
step3: {
  UserCode -> Kernel: "epoll_wait(epfd, events, MAX, -1)"
  Kernel -> UserCode: "returns: events[0].data.fd=7, events=EPOLLIN\n[data available in receive buffer]"
  UserCode -> Kernel: "read(fd=7, buf, BUF_SIZE) → n=512"
  UserCode -> Kernel: "write(fd=7, buf, 512) → echo"
}
step4: {
  UserCode -> Kernel: "epoll_wait(...)"
  Kernel -> UserCode: "returns: events[0].data.fd=7, events=EPOLLIN"
  UserCode -> Kernel: "read(fd=7, buf, BUF_SIZE) → n=0 (EOF)\npeer closed write side"
}
safe_del: "⚠ MANDATORY ORDER: DEL before close" {
  style: {
    fill: "#fff3cd"
    stroke: "#f0a500"
    stroke-width: 3
    font-color: "#7a4f00"
    bold: true
  }
}
step5: {
  UserCode -> Kernel: "epoll_ctl(epfd, EPOLL_CTL_DEL, fd=7, NULL)\n→ fd=7 removed from interest set ✓"
  Kernel -> UserCode: "return 0 (success)"
}
step6: {
  UserCode -> Kernel: "close(fd=7)\n→ kernel decrements file-description refcount"
  Kernel -> OS: "refcount reaches 0:\nfile description freed"
  OS -> Kernel: "fd=7 slot returned to\nfree list (lowest available)"
}
step7: {
  UserCode -> Kernel: "accept4(listen_fd, ...) [new client connects]"
  Kernel -> OS: "allocate lowest free fd"
  OS -> Kernel: "fd=7 (recycled!)"
  Kernel -> UserCode: "returns fd=7 (NEW connection)"
  UserCode -> Kernel: "epoll_ctl(EPOLL_CTL_ADD, fd=7, {EPOLLIN})\n→ new connection registered ✓"
}
trap_warning: |md
  ## 🔴 fd-Reuse Trap: The Silent Bug
  **Scenario if step 5 (DEL) is SKIPPED:**
  1. `close(fd=7)` — old connection closed
  2. `accept4()` → OS recycles fd=7 for new client
  3. `epoll_ctl(EPOLL_CTL_ADD, fd=7, ...)` → **EEXIST** (fd=7 still in interest set!)
  4. OR: later `epoll_ctl(EPOLL_CTL_DEL, fd=7, NULL)` **removes the NEW connection**
  **Why hard to reproduce:** Only triggers when OS recycles fd numbers
  between the skip and the subsequent ADD/DEL — requires high connection
  churn. Works fine under low load; corrupts state under C10K benchmark.
  **Fix:** Always call `epoll_ctl(DEL, fd, NULL)` **before** `close(fd)`.
| {
  near: bottom-center
  style: {
    fill: "#fff0f0"
    stroke: "#cc0000"
    stroke-width: 3
    font-color: "#4a0000"
  }
}